### Step 1: Define the Custom Element

Create a new JavaScript file or add a script tag in your HTML file. In this script, you'll define a new custom element.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Custom Element Example</title>
</head>
<body>

<my-input></my-input>

<script>
class MyInput extends HTMLElement {
    constructor() {
        super();
        // Attach a shadow root to the element.
        this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' });

        // Create elements
        const wrapper = document.createElement('div');
        const input = document.createElement('input');
        const button = document.createElement('button');

        // Set attributes
        input.type = 'text';
        button.textContent = 'Submit';

        // Append elements to the shadow root
        wrapper.appendChild(input);
        wrapper.appendChild(button);
        this.shadowRoot.appendChild(wrapper);

        // Add event listener to the button
        button.addEventListener('click', () => {
            alert(`You entered: ${input.value}`);
        });
    }
}

// Define the new element
customElements.define('my-input', MyInput);
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation

1. **Custom Element Class**: The `MyInput` class extends `HTMLElement`. This is the base class for all custom elements.

2. **Shadow DOM**: The `attachShadow` method creates a shadow root for the element. This encapsulates the element's DOM and styles, preventing them from leaking out or being affected by the global styles.

3. **Element Creation**: Inside the constructor, we create a `div`, an `input`, and a `button`. These are the components of our custom element.

4. **Event Handling**: We add a click event listener to the button. When the button is clicked, it displays an alert with the text entered in the input field.

5. **Defining the Element**: The `customElements.define` method registers the new element with the browser. The first argument is the tag name of the element, and the second argument is the class that defines its behavior.

### Usage

Once defined, you can use the `<my-input>` element anywhere in your HTML. It will render a text input and a button, and clicking the button will show an alert with the input's value.
